"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 21–24
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2chronicles-21-24.py

Ch 21: Jehoram — the Ahab-dynasty son-in-law; fratricidal succession;
  Edom and Libnah revolt; Elijah's letter (unique epistolary form);
  the Philistine-Arabian raids; ignominious death by bowel disease.

Ch 22: Ahaziah and Athaliah — Ahaziah caught in Jehu's coup;
  Athaliah's usurpation (unprecedented female seizure of Judah's throne);
  Joash hidden in the temple by Jehoshabeath for 6 years.

Ch 23: Jehoiada's coup — priestly-led restoration of Joash;
  the Levitical guard; covenant at the temple; Baal's shrine destroyed;
  worship re-ordered on dual Mosaic-Davidic authority.

Ch 24: Joash — temple repair and collection chest; Jehoiada's burial
  among kings; apostasy after the priest's death; Zechariah's martyrdom
  (cited by Jesus in Matt 23:35); Aramean invasion; Joash assassinated
  by servants with Ammonite/Moabite maternal descent.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>The Davidic succession formula — &lsquo;rested with his ancestors and was buried with them in the city of David&rsquo; — is the standard Chronicler burial-honor report. Jehoshaphat receives an honorable burial; his son Jehoram will receive a contrasting dishonor (v19-20: no burial fire, buried but not in the royal tombs). The dynastic continuity of burial in the city of David (the royal necropolis from David through the divided monarchy) was an important mark of legitimacy and divine favor. Only kings who preserved covenant loyalty were typically buried in David&rsquo;s royal tombs; the exceptions and exclusions carry heavy theological weight throughout Chronicles.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s six other sons — Azariah, Jehiel, Zechariah, Azariah (a second), Michael, and Shephatiah — represent the vulnerable Davidic line that Jehoram will eliminate. The Chronicler&rsquo;s list of names (expanded from the 2 Kings account) individualizes the fratricidal victims: they were not anonymous collateral damage but named sons of the covenant family. The note that they were &lsquo;sons of the king of Israel&rsquo; (i.e., of Judah&rsquo;s king) may reflect the Chronicler&rsquo;s use of &lsquo;Israel&rsquo; as a theological designation for the covenant people, not the northern kingdom — Jehoshaphat was king of all Israel in the Chronicler&rsquo;s understanding.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s distribution of gifts and fortified cities to his younger sons was standard ANE practice for managing a large royal family while ensuring the succession of the designated heir. Similar provisions appear in Mesopotamian royal wills and Egyptian royal succession documents: the king distributed estates, valuables, and administrative responsibilities among non-inheriting sons to give them status without threatening the primary heir. The fortified cities in Judah given to the princes created semi-independent princely domains within the kingdom — a feudal arrangement that kept the dynasty&rsquo;s members occupied with regional governance. The explicit notice that the kingdom went to Jehoram as the firstborn establishes the legitimacy of his accession by birth-order rather than royal appointment.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Jehoram&rsquo;s elimination of his brothers and some Israelite officials reflects the brutal dynastic politics common at succession moments throughout the ancient Near East. Abimelech killed seventy brothers to secure Shechem (Judg 9:5); Baasha killed the entire house of Jeroboam (1 Kgs 15:29); Zimri killed all of Baasha&rsquo;s household (1 Kgs 16:11-12). In Mesopotamia, Esarhaddon&rsquo;s brothers fled when Sennacherib designated him heir, and they later assassinated their father. Fratricidal succession was the dark underside of ANE monarchy — the stronger the dynastic investment in a single line, the more dangerous for those not in the chosen line. Jehoram&rsquo;s murders mark the beginning of his reign with blood and covenant-disloyalty.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Jehoram&rsquo;s eight-year reign (ca. 848-841 BCE) and his thirty-two-year age at accession mean he died at forty — cut short, the Chronicler implies, by his sins. The synchronism with the northern kingdom (he reigned as Ahab&rsquo;s dynasty peaked in the north, parallel to Jehoram/Joram of Israel) placed Judah under the gravitational pull of the Omride-Ahab dynasty&rsquo;s theology and political culture during this period. The coregency with his father Jehoshaphat (implied by the 1 Kgs 22:50 and 2 Kgs 8:16 chronology) makes exact dates complex; the Chronicler&rsquo;s focus is theological trajectory rather than regnal precision.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Jehoram&rsquo;s marriage to Athaliah, daughter of Ahab (and presumably Jezebel), was the political fruit of the Jehoshaphat-Ahab alliance (2 Chr 18). The dynastic intermarriage policy was the standard ANE mechanism for sealing political alliances — Egyptian kings cemented treaties with Mitanni, Hatti, and Babylon through royal marriage; Omri&rsquo;s Israel allied with Phoenician Tyre through Ahab&rsquo;s marriage to Jezebel. But what secured alliances also transferred religious influences: Jezebel&rsquo;s Baal-worship moved through Ahab&rsquo;s court and then through Athaliah into Judah. The Chronicler&rsquo;s theological diagnosis — he followed the house of Ahab because his wife was from Ahab&rsquo;s house — identifies the cultural-religious mechanism of apostasy: foreign royal wives reshaped the covenant community&rsquo;s religious identity (cf. Solomon&rsquo;s foreign wives, 2 Chr 11:21).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The lamp-of-David guarantee is explicit: &lsquo;YHWH was not willing to destroy the house of David, because of the covenant he had made with David, and since he had promised to give a lamp (<em>nîr</em>) to him and to his sons forever.&rsquo; The &lsquo;lamp&rsquo; idiom (<em>nîr</em>) appears in 1 Kgs 11:36 (for Rehoboam); 15:4 (for Abijah); 2 Kgs 8:19 — it is consistently the covenant-guarantee that YHWH will preserve a dynasty despite individual sin. The lamp image comes from the eternal-fire language: YHWH will not extinguish the Davidic line. The Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience, living without a Davidic king, found in this guarantee the basis for hope — YHWH had preserved the line through worse than exile before.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Edom&rsquo;s revolt from Judahite control reflects the political reality of the late 9th century BCE. David had conquered Edom (2 Sam 8:13-14; 1 Chr 18:12-13) and placed Israelite garrisons throughout the country. The Edomite subjugation had already been threatened under Solomon (1 Kgs 11:14-22: Hadad the Edomite as Solomon&rsquo;s adversary) and was temporarily restored under Jehoshaphat. Now, as Judah weakened under Jehoram, Edom seized its opportunity. The geographical context matters: Edom controlled the King&rsquo;s Highway and the Arabah trade routes to the Red Sea port of Ezion-geber — loss of Edom meant loss of the southern trade network and access to Red Sea commerce.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Jehoram&rsquo;s night breakout (<em>waYYāqom laYYĕlāh waYYAK eT-ʾĕḏôm</em>) from Edomite encirclement is militarily ambiguous — 2 Kgs 8:21 also preserves the episode without clarity about who won. The phrase &lsquo;struck the Edomites who surrounded him and his chariot commanders&rsquo; may mean Jehoram broke through the siege rather than defeated Edom decisively. The result (v10: Edom remained independent) confirms no lasting Judahite victory. The night raid was a standard ANE military tactic for breaking sieges — Sennacherib&rsquo;s Annals describe night attacks and surprise breakouts in comparable terrain; the ambush-and-encirclement pattern in the Transjordanian hill country was well-suited to this type of irregular warfare.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Edom&rsquo;s successful independence is attributed to Jehoram&rsquo;s religious apostasy: &lsquo;because he had forsaken YHWH the God of his ancestors.&rsquo; The explanatory aside shows the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological methodology: geopolitical reversals (Edom independent, Libnah revolting) are the external expressions of covenant breach. Libnah was a Levitical city (Josh 21:13) in the Shephelah southwest of Jerusalem — its revolt may indicate the Philistine-allied territory was reasserting non-Judahite identity, or it reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s knowledge of a local administrative rebellion. The simultaneous loss of Edom (east) and Libnah (west) signals the geopolitical unraveling of Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s extensive empire under his unfaithful son.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The high places on the hill country of Judah and the seduction (<em>zānāh</em>, to fornicate/go astray) of Jerusalem into spiritual prostitution reflects the standard Deuteronomic language for syncretism. High places (<em>bāmôT</em>) were local hill-top worship sites; their spread under Jehoram reversed the cultic centralization policy. The term <em>zānāh</em> (used here for religious unfaithfulness) is borrowed from the prophetic tradition (Hosea, Jeremiah, Ezekiel) where Israel&rsquo;s covenant infidelity is described as prostitution — the covenant was a marriage, so idolatry was adultery. The Chronicler uses the term carefully: the seduction came from the king, not from the people spontaneously — royal apostasy as the mechanism of popular apostasy.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s letter to Jehoram is the only instance in the biblical record of a written prophetic communication from Elijah. Prophets typically delivered oracles orally, in person. The letter raises chronological questions: Elijah was translated ca. 848 BCE (the beginning of Jehoram&rsquo;s reign), so the letter may have been written before his translation and delivered posthumously — a prophetic document addressing a future king. Alternatively, the Chronicler may use &lsquo;Elijah&rsquo; in a slightly different chronological framework than Kings. The letter&rsquo;s authenticity has been debated by scholars, but its content (accusation of forsaking David&rsquo;s God, following Ahab&rsquo;s house, murdering brothers) is consistent with Elijah&rsquo;s prophetic tradition.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s accusation that Jehoram had &lsquo;seduced Judah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem, just as the house of Ahab seduced Israel&rsquo; makes explicit the structural parallel the Chronicler has been building: Jehoram = Ahab of the south. The Ahab-dynasty theology (Baal worship, royal murder, economic exploitation of subjects) has been exported to Judah through the Jehoshaphat-Ahab marriage alliance. Elijah&rsquo;s earlier confrontation with Ahab (1 Kgs 18-21) now has a southern echo: the prophet who stood against Ahab in the north sends his written word against Ahab&rsquo;s son-in-law in the south. The pattern of prophetic accountability transcending geographic and dynastic lines is a key Chronicler theme.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The threatened plague on Jehoram&rsquo;s people, children, wives, and possessions before the personal disease on the king himself follows the Deuteronomic punishment structure of Deut 28 (the covenant curses move from individual to family to nation). The specific sequence — external raids (vv16-17), personal disease (vv18-19), death in pain (v19) — enacts the prophetic announcement precisely. The ANE pattern of prophetic-curse-fulfillment (the word of the prophet as the activating agent of divine judgment) is central to the Chronicler&rsquo;s theology of history: YHWH&rsquo;s word through his prophets does not return empty (Isa 55:11 — though this is Isaiah rather than the Chronicler, the principle is shared).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The bowel disease that would cause Jehoram&rsquo;s intestines to come out (&lsquo;until your bowels come out because of the sickness, day by day&rsquo;) is a severe and unusual judgment. Medical historians have suggested chronic dysentery, inflammatory bowel disease, or intestinal cancer as possible identifications. The two-year course (v19: &lsquo;after two years&rsquo;) and the terminal prolapse are consistent with a severe intestinal pathology. The Chronicler&rsquo;s recording of this specific medical detail serves a theological purpose: the king who used his reign to eliminate his brothers and destroy covenant loyalty died in a degrading physical dissolution — the ultimate covenant-curse reversal of the royal body that should have been the embodiment of YHWH&rsquo;s blessing.</p>",
    "16": "<p>YHWH stirred up (<em>ʿûr</em>) the hostility of the Philistines and the Arabians against Jehoram — the verb&rsquo;s use of divine agency for geopolitical movements is characteristic of the Chronicler&rsquo;s historiography. The Philistines occupied the southwestern coastal plain; the Arabians who bordered the Cushites were the nomadic Arab tribes of the Negev and Sinai desert zone. Both groups had been subdued or had given tribute to Jehoshaphat (2 Chr 17:11); their renewed hostility under Jehoram reflects the geopolitical reality that Judah&rsquo;s weakness invited border raids. This pattern — prosperity under covenant-faithful kings, raiding and tribute cessation under apostate kings — is the Chronicler&rsquo;s signature geopolitical theology.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Philistine-Arabian raid carried off &lsquo;all the possessions found in the palace of the king, and also his sons and his wives&rsquo; — leaving only Ahaziah, the youngest son. The near-total elimination of the Davidic royal family at one stroke (v17 from raiders, v18-19 Jehoram by disease) brings the covenant line to the edge of extinction. The single surviving son, Ahaziah, will himself be killed by Jehu (22:9), leaving only the infant Joash hidden in the temple (22:11-12). The Chronicler presents these chapters as a multi-generational near-extinction event for the Davidic covenant promise — the drama of YHWH&rsquo;s faithfulness to preserve a lamp for David even when the wick is nearly consumed.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The incurable bowel disease begins as the fulfillment of Elijah&rsquo;s prophecy. The term <em>neḥlāh</em> (incurable, not curable) — the same word used for Asa&rsquo;s foot disease (2 Chr 16:12: &lsquo;until in his disease he did not seek YHWH but physicians&rsquo;) — marks this as a divine judgment beyond medical remedy. In the ancient world, disease was understood within a framework of divine causation: when the gods sent illness, no human healer could counteract it. The Chronicler&rsquo;s mention of &lsquo;incurable disease&rsquo; signals to the reader that no intervention (human or priestly) would reverse the judgment — Elijah&rsquo;s word was sovereign.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Jehoram&rsquo;s death &lsquo;in great agony&rsquo; (<em>bĕlōʾ-ḥemdāh</em>, literally &lsquo;without desire/regret&rsquo; — the Hebrew may also mean without lamentation-fires) and the absence of burial-fire honor represents the maximum dishonor in the Chronicler&rsquo;s burial-rating system. Burial fires (<em>śĕrêpāh</em>) — aromatic fires at the burial of kings — are mentioned positively for Asa (2 Chr 16:14) and Hezekiah (2 Chr 32:33). Their absence for Jehoram means the people did not perform the customary royal mourning rites. The phrase &lsquo;to no one&rsquo;s regret&rsquo; (<em>wĕlōʾ niklāh</em>) or &lsquo;without being missed&rsquo; is the ultimate verdict on a king: not just that he died badly, but that no one mourned his passing.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The double mention of his age (32 at accession, 8 years of reign) and the burial notice (&lsquo;but not in the tombs of the kings&rsquo;) delivers the verdict: Jehoram was buried in the city of David but excluded from the royal necropolis that held the honored Davidic kings. The spatial distinction between burial in Jerusalem and burial in the royal tomb complex was socially and theologically significant in the ancient world — location of burial indicated status, honor, and community. Being buried in Jerusalem proper but outside the royal tombs was a compromise position: the Davidic line required his presence in the city, but covenant faithfulness denied him full royal burial honor. This precise gradation of burial honor is a distinctively Chronicler concern.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>The residents of Jerusalem made Ahaziah king — an unusual phrasing suggesting popular affirmation rather than standard dynastic succession. The reason: all older sons had been killed by the Arabians (v17 of ch21). The Arabians&rsquo; raid, which devastated Jehoram&rsquo;s household, left only the youngest son Ahaziah as heir. The political situation — a surviving youngest son with no older siblings — was precarious by ANE standards. In Mesopotamian succession practice, the youngest son inheriting after the death of all older brothers raised questions of legitimacy that required public affirmation. The Jerusalem community&rsquo;s installation of Ahaziah represents that affirmation.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The age forty-two at accession is almost certainly a textual error or different tradition from 2 Kgs 8:26 (which gives twenty-two). The problem: if Ahaziah was forty-two and his father Jehoram died at forty (8 years of reign beginning at age thirty-two), then Ahaziah would be older than his father — chronologically impossible. Most scholars accept the 2 Kings figure of twenty-two; the forty-two in Chronicles may be a scribal transposition (dalet for resh in Hebrew) or a different numerical tradition. The Chronicler&rsquo;s text preserves an acknowledged difficulty; the LXX and some manuscripts read twenty here. His mother Athaliah was a granddaughter of Omri — confirming the dynastic link: Jehoram&rsquo;s wife was from Ahab&rsquo;s house, and Omri was Ahab&rsquo;s father.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Athaliah&rsquo;s role as royal counselor to her son represents the institutionalized position of the <em>gĕbîrāh</em> (queen mother) in Israelite and Judahite court life. The queen mother had official standing in the royal court — she had her own seat (1 Kgs 2:19: Bathsheba&rsquo;s throne beside Solomon), her own title and household, and significant political influence. In the ANE, the queen mother&rsquo;s role was formally recognized in Mesopotamian courts (the <em>ummi šarri</em>, mother of the king), Hittite royal succession documents, and Egyptian court records. Athaliah&rsquo;s function as &lsquo;counselor in wickedness&rsquo; gives the standard queen-mother role its most malignant expression: instead of providing wise counsel, she guided her son toward the Ahab-dynasty theology.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The advisors from the house of Ahab who counseled Ahaziah after his father&rsquo;s death represent the network of Omride-trained officials who had penetrated Judah&rsquo;s court through the Jehoshaphat-Ahab alliance. These were not merely foreign visitors but embedded court officials whose political loyalties remained with the northern Ahab dynasty even while serving in Jerusalem. The institutional penetration of Judah&rsquo;s government by Ahab-house loyalists explains why Athaliah could seize the throne so efficiently when Ahaziah was killed — the infrastructure was already in place. The Chronicler&rsquo;s diagnosis is institutional: it was not just a bad king (Ahaziah) but a corrupted court system that made his reign possible and his replacement by Athaliah conceivable.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Ramoth-gilead campaign was the defining geopolitical conflict of the period. Ramoth-gilead (Tell Ramith in the Gilead plateau) was a strategically critical city on the King&rsquo;s Highway — whoever held it controlled the major north-south trade route east of the Jordan. Ahab had sought to retake it from the Arameans (2 Chr 18; 1 Kgs 22) and died in the attempt. Now Jehoram of Israel (Ahab&rsquo;s son) and Ahaziah of Judah (Ahab&rsquo;s grandson through Athaliah) continue the campaign. Hazael had recently usurped the Aramean throne (2 Kgs 8:7-15: Hazael smothered Ben-hadad) and represented a more aggressive Syrian policy. The wound Jehoram received at Ramoth-gilead created the vulnerability that allowed Jehu&rsquo;s coup.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Joram&rsquo;s withdrawal to Jezreel to recover from his wounds while Jehu remained at Ramoth-gilead with the army set the stage for Jehu&rsquo;s coup. Jezreel was the Omride dynasty&rsquo;s secondary capital in the Valley of Jezreel (the primary capital was Samaria). The royal compound at Jezreel was where Naboth&rsquo;s vineyard had been (1 Kgs 21), now the site of Jehoram&rsquo;s convalescence. Ahaziah&rsquo;s visit to his wounded uncle at Jezreel was a standard duty-visit — the nephew visiting his injured ally — but it placed him in precisely the wrong location when Jehu&rsquo;s forces arrived.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&lsquo;Ahaziah&rsquo;s downfall came about through God&rsquo;s design&rsquo; (<em>mēʾĕlōhîm hāyĕtāh tĕbûsāT ʾăḥazyāhû</em>) — the Chronicler explicitly frames Ahaziah&rsquo;s death as divine arrangement, not merely political misfortune. Jehu&rsquo;s commission from Elisha (2 Kgs 9:1-10: the anointing of Jehu as YHWH&rsquo;s instrument of judgment on the house of Ahab) means that Ahaziah&rsquo;s association with Ahab&rsquo;s house brought him under the scope of the judgment on Ahab&rsquo;s house. This is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most explicit use of the divine-design language in a political narrative: what appeared to be Ahaziah&rsquo;s diplomatic visit becoming a death trap was arranged by YHWH&rsquo;s sovereign purposes.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Jehu&rsquo;s killing of &lsquo;the princes of Judah and the sons of Ahaziah&rsquo;s brothers who were attendants of Ahaziah&rsquo; reflects the scope of the Ahab-dynasty purge. Jehu&rsquo;s coup (2 Kgs 9-10) was a thorough political revolution: he killed Jehoram of Israel, Ahaziah of Judah, and seventy sons of Ahab, and then executed the Baal-worshipers in the Baal temple of Samaria (2 Kgs 10:18-28). The sons of Ahaziah&rsquo;s brothers serving in the Judahite court at the time of his visit to Jezreel were swept up in the general purge of Ahab-dynasty affiliates. Their deaths, like Ahaziah&rsquo;s, were the fruit of the Jehoshaphat-Ahab marriage alliance.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Ahaziah&rsquo;s death at Jehu&rsquo;s hands is described differently in Chronicles (found hiding in Samaria, brought to Jehu, executed) than in 2 Kings 9:27 (fled to Megiddo, wounded at the ascent of Gur, died at Megiddo). The variant accounts may reflect different source traditions or different stages of the same event. Both accounts agree on Jehu as the agent and Ahaziah&rsquo;s death as the result. The Chronicles notice that Ahaziah received burial respect (&lsquo;because he was the grandson of Jehoshaphat, who sought the LORD with all his heart&rsquo;) is unique to the Chronicler and reflects his key theological principle: Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s covenant faithfulness earned ongoing benefits that extended to his unfaithful descendants.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Athaliah&rsquo;s seizure of the Judahite throne upon her son&rsquo;s death was unprecedented in the history of the Davidic monarchy — no woman had previously ruled Judah as monarch. Female regents were not unknown in the broader ANE: Hatshepsut of Egypt ruled as pharaoh (ca. 1479-1458 BCE); Sammuramat (the historical basis for the Semiramis legend) served as Assyrian regent for her young son Adad-nirari III ca. 811-806 BCE; Nitocris was a regent in Babylon. Athaliah&rsquo;s action of destroying &lsquo;all the royal seed of the house of Judah&rsquo; mirrors the standard ANE dynastic-change practice: to secure a usurper&rsquo;s position, eliminate all potential legitimate claimants. Jehu had done exactly this in Israel (2 Kgs 10:1-11). Athaliah applies the same logic to Judah.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Jehoshabeath&rsquo;s rescue of the infant Joash is the hinge on which the entire Davidic covenant turns in the Chronicler&rsquo;s narrative. She is identified as the daughter of King Jehoram and wife of Jehoiada the priest — uniquely positioned at the intersection of royal and priestly families. Her ability to remove Joash &lsquo;from among the king&rsquo;s sons who were being murdered&rsquo; implies access to the royal nursery, presumably through her relationship with the royal household. The hiding place — the house of God — was the one location where Athaliah&rsquo;s writ was most politically complicated: the temple staff (controlled by Jehoiada) provided institutional protection for the child. The temple as sanctuary for the vulnerable is an ANE theme: both Egyptian and Mesopotamian temples had asylum functions.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Six years of concealment in the temple complex preserved the Davidic line through its most precarious historical moment. The number six (one year short of seven, the number of completion) carries structural weight: the hidden king&rsquo;s seventh year (23:1) is when the restoration comes. The six years parallel the six days before the Sabbath, the six years before the Sabbatical year — the period of hiddenness before the revelation of the rightful heir. During those six years, Athaliah ruled Judah, the Baal cult presumably continued under Omride influence, and the legitimate king sat hidden in the sacred space that his ancestor David had established. The theological drama is maximally compressed: the lamp of David (2 Chr 21:7) hidden in the lamp-house of YHWH.</p>"
  },
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>In the seventh year Jehoiada &lsquo;took courage&rsquo; (<em>waYYitḥaZzEQ</em> — strengthened himself) and entered into a covenant with five captains of hundreds. The seventh year is theologically significant — the year of release, of completion, of restoration in Israelite legal thinking. The covenant Jehoiada makes with the military commanders is a conspiratorial pact before revealing the hidden king — standard practice for palace coups in the ancient world. Assyrian records describe similar conspiratorial covenants among palace officials before succession crises. The five captains (named — Azariah son of Jeroham, Ishmael son of Jehohanan, Azariah son of Obed, Maaseiah son of Adaiah, Elishaphat son of Zichri) are individually identified, making this historically concrete rather than a generic coup narrative.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Levites and heads of ancestral houses gathered from throughout Judah and came to Jerusalem — the all-Israel assembly pattern that the Chronicler uses for the most significant moments of covenant renewal (Solomon&rsquo;s temple dedication, Hezekiah&rsquo;s Passover, Josiah&rsquo;s covenant renewal). The involvement of both the Levites (the religious professionals scattered through the Levitical cities) and the heads of ancestral houses (the tribal/clan leadership) creates a legitimate assembly: this was not merely a military coup but a national covenant-restoration backed by the full religious and social establishment of Judah.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The assembly&rsquo;s covenant in the house of God (<em>baYYiT hāʾĕlōhîm</em>) — that the king&rsquo;s son (Joash) would reign as YHWH had promised concerning the sons of David — grounds the political restoration in the Davidic covenant theology. The covenant made in the temple positions this as a sacred oath, not merely a political agreement. The reference to &lsquo;what YHWH spoke concerning the sons of David&rsquo; is the Davidic covenant promise of 2 Sam 7 / 1 Chr 17 — the eternal dynasty. By invoking this promise, Jehoiada frames the restoration of Joash as the fulfillment of YHWH&rsquo;s own commitment rather than human political preference.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The military organization of the restoration — one-third of the priests and Levites on Sabbath duty at the gatekeeping posts, one-third at the palace, one-third at the Foundation Gate — is a sophisticated deployment plan that uses the existing temple duty-roster as cover for positioning forces throughout the strategic points of Jerusalem. The use of the Sabbath turnover (when both the outgoing and incoming guard divisions were present) doubled the available personnel at the critical moment. This tactical use of religious routine is attested in military history: the Maccabean revolt similarly exploited religious assembly points for military organization.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The three-point deployment (temple gatekeeping posts, palace, Foundation Gate) controlled the three axes of access to the sacred precinct and the royal compound. The Foundation Gate (&lsquo;gate of the Sur&rsquo; in 2 Kgs 11:6) was likely on the southern or western side of the temple mount. The &lsquo;all the people&rsquo; in the temple courts served as the public witness and acclamation element of the coronation — in ANE coronation ceremonies, the assembled people&rsquo;s acclaim was an essential legitimating element. Without popular witness, a coronation could be contested; with all the people in the courts, Joash&rsquo;s coronation would be unassailable.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The strict control of access (&lsquo;no one is to enter the LORD&rsquo;s house except the priests and Levites on duty — they are holy; all the rest of the people shall maintain the LORD&rsquo;s watch&rsquo;) ensured that the coup had a legitimate sacred character rather than a political mob character. The holiness-boundary maintained at the temple entrance — only the consecrated may enter the sacred space — was simultaneously a security measure (limiting who could approach the child king) and a theological statement (the restoration of the rightful king was a holy act protected by YHWH&rsquo;s sanctuary). The weapons were in the hands of the guard, not the general public.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Levitical guard surrounding the king, with weapons in hand, ready to kill anyone who approached — a sacred-space security detail. The Levites&rsquo; historical function included temple policing (Num 18:2-7: &lsquo;you and your sons will watch over your priesthood for everything concerning the altar and inside the veil; and you shall serve.&rsquo; Anyone who approaches shall be put to death&rsquo;). The Chronicler&rsquo;s narrative assigns the armed guard role to the Levites (while 2 Kgs 11:9 assigns it to the officers), reflecting his consistent emphasis on Levitical responsibility for temple security and order.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The exact execution of Jehoiada&rsquo;s plan — each captain taking his men (both incoming and outgoing Sabbath-shift) — reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s interest in showing that this restoration succeeded because of meticulous obedience to the priest&rsquo;s instructions. The priest Jehoiada did not dismiss any of the divisions: he doubled the available forces by keeping the outgoing division rather than releasing them after the Sabbath handover. This military pragmatism combined with religious protocol is the Chronicler&rsquo;s ideal: proper attention to both the sacred order (maintaining the Sabbath division system) and the practical need (using double forces for the critical moment).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The weapons Jehoiada distributed to the captains — spears, bucklers (<em>māginnîm</em>), and shields (<em>šĕlāṭîm</em>) — had belonged to King David and were stored in the house of God. David&rsquo;s royal armory in the temple complex (described in 2 Sam 8:7; 1 Chr 18:7 as the gold shields taken from Hadadezer&rsquo;s servants) represented the accumulated military trophies of Israel&rsquo;s greatest king. Using David&rsquo;s weapons for the restoration of David&rsquo;s line had powerful symbolic resonance: the Davidic covenant was being enforced using Davidic resources. The temple as armory was common in the ancient Near East — temple treasuries held both precious vessels and military equipment.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The positioning of armed guards from the south side to the north side of the temple, along the altar and the house, created a protective perimeter around the entire temple complex with the child-king at its center. The compass-point description (south side to north side) signals that the protection was total — no exposed flank. The people standing with weapons &lsquo;beside the king, all around him&rsquo; created a protective ring of human shields as well as armed sentinels at the perimeter. This dual-layer security (perimeter guards at the walls + close guard around the king) reflects sophisticated security practice for a high-value political asset.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The coronation elements — the crown (<em>haNNēzer</em>), the testimony (<em>hāʿēḏût</em>), the anointing (<em>waYYimšĕḥû</em>), and the acclamation (&lsquo;Long live the king!&rsquo;) — are the four components of legitimate Israelite coronation. The &lsquo;testimony&rsquo; given to the king is most likely a copy of the Torah (Deut 17:18-19 requires the king to write a copy of the law; cf. Ps 2:7 where the king receives YHWH&rsquo;s &lsquo;decree&rsquo;). In Egyptian coronation rites, the new pharaoh received the royal titulary and the crook-and-flail at the coronation; in Mesopotamia, the king received the divine commission before the assembly. Israel&rsquo;s coronation combines the sacred document (testimony/torah) with the political symbols (crown) and the sacral rite (anointing with oil).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Athaliah&rsquo;s hearing &lsquo;the noise of the people running and praising the king&rsquo; and coming to the temple reflects her likely location in the palace complex adjacent to the temple mount. The sound of the people (<em>qôl hāʿām rāṣîm wĕhallĕlîm ʾeT-haMelek</em>) — the shout of celebration — was the public announcement that a new king had been proclaimed. In ANE coronation contexts, the acclamation shout was the key public signal that transferred political legitimacy. Athaliah&rsquo;s arrival at the temple after hearing this shout shows her recognition that the political event had already occurred — she was responding to a fait accompli rather than preventing one.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Athaliah saw the king &lsquo;standing by his pillar at the entrance&rsquo; — the Chronicler uses the pillar (<em>ʿammûd</em>) as the king&rsquo;s designated ceremonial position in the temple. The royal pillar at the temple entrance appears in 2 Kgs 11:14; 23:3 as a fixed feature of royal-temple ceremonies. The trumpets beside the king and the princes and the people of the land rejoicing to the sound of trumpets describe a completed coronation ceremony already in progress. The Levitical singers with musical instruments were performing the coronation liturgy (cf. the coronation psalms — Ps 2, 21, 45, 72). Athaliah&rsquo;s tearing her clothes and crying &lsquo;Treason! Treason!&rsquo; is the reaction of a deposed usurper recognizing the legitimacy of what she cannot reverse.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Jehoiada&rsquo;s command to remove Athaliah from the temple precinct before execution reflects the law of sanctuary: the temple was not to be defiled with blood. The Chronicler&rsquo;s concern for the sanctity of the temple space — no bloodshed within its precincts — was a standing legal principle in the ancient world. Mesopotamian temples had sanctuary laws that protected individuals within the sacred precinct; Israelite cities of refuge (Num 35:9-15; Deut 19:1-13) extended this principle beyond temples. Jehoiada&rsquo;s removal of Athaliah before execution maintained the ritual purity of the temple while accomplishing the political necessity. Anyone who followed her into the temple was to be killed by the sword — protecting the sacred space from becoming a site of political asylum for the usurper&rsquo;s supporters.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Athaliah&rsquo;s execution at the Horse Gate at the palace represents the deliberate inversion of the temple-palace relationship: she entered the sacred space (temple) from the palace, was ejected from the sacred space, and was executed at the place where the palace and the city intersected. The Horse Gate in Jerusalem was in the southeastern section of the city (Neh 3:28; Jer 31:40), near the junction of the palace complex and the city&rsquo;s lower sections. Death at this location — the palace&rsquo;s functional boundary, not its honored inner courts — was appropriate for a usurper: she died neither within the sacred precinct nor within the royal palace but at the liminal threshold between them.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Jehoiada made a covenant between himself, all the people, and the king — a three-party covenant that re-established the Sinai relationship: YHWH, people, and king in right order. The covenant formula &lsquo;that they would be the LORD&rsquo;s people&rsquo; is the fundamental covenant declaration (Lev 26:12; Jer 7:23; 11:4; Ezek 36:28: &lsquo;you shall be my people and I will be your God&rsquo;). The Sinai covenant was always described as a three-party relationship between YHWH, the mediator (Moses/the king), and the people. Jehoiada&rsquo;s covenant restores this structure after six years in which Athaliah&rsquo;s Baal-oriented rule had created a rival three-party relationship (Baal, Athaliah, the people she seduced).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The immediate popular destruction of Baal&rsquo;s temple, altars, and images reflects the covenant renewal&rsquo;s practical consequence: the Baal cult established under Athaliah&rsquo;s influence (presumably following the Omride template of formal Baal worship) was eliminated. The Baal temple in Jerusalem was likely established during Athaliah&rsquo;s six-year reign as an institutional expression of Omride religious policy — the same Baal worship Elijah had confronted at Carmel. Mattan the Baal priest killed before the altars mirrors the elimination of Baal&rsquo;s prophets at Kishon (1 Kgs 18:40). The pattern is deliberate: the restoration of the Davidic king required the purge of the rival cult — as David&rsquo;s kingdom had required the defeat of Saul&rsquo;s opponents before Solomon built the temple.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jehoiada&rsquo;s restoration of the temple administration under the Levitical divisions David had organized reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent theme: legitimate temple worship rests on dual authority — Mosaic law (the instruction of Moses) and Davidic liturgical organization. The two-authority structure (Moses + David) appears throughout Chronicles as the foundation of correct worship (1 Chr 23-26 describes David&rsquo;s organizational work; 2 Chr 5:13 and 8:14 describe its implementation by Solomon). After six years of disruption under Athaliah&rsquo;s Baal-friendly regime, Jehoiada resets the system to its canonical form: Levitical divisions as David arranged, burnt offerings as Moses commanded, with joy and singing as David had established.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The gatekeepers stationed at the temple entrances to prevent entry by the ritually unclean is a post-exilic concern the Chronicler retro-projects onto the restoration narrative. The concern about ritual purity at the temple gate — &lsquo;that no one who was unclean in any way might enter&rsquo; — reflects the Holiness Code (Lev 15-16) and was reinforced in the post-exilic period by Nehemiah&rsquo;s assignment of Levitical gatekeepers (Neh 13:19-22). The restoration of proper gatekeeping after Athaliah&rsquo;s reign is one of Jehoiada&rsquo;s first administrative acts — suggesting that during her reign, the temple access controls had deteriorated along with everything else.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The coronation procession from the temple to the palace — through the upper gate, down through the palace, and to the king&rsquo;s throne — replicates the standard ANE coronation route. In Mesopotamian practice, the new king was installed in the temple before being installed on the palace throne — the divine legitimation preceded the political enthronement. Jehoiada&rsquo;s procession includes the captains of hundreds, the nobles, the governors (<em>môšĕlîm</em>), and all the people of the land — the full social hierarchy in order (military, aristocratic, administrative, popular). This ordered procession represents the re-establishment of legitimate social order after the chaos of Athaliah&rsquo;s usurpation.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The city&rsquo;s peace after Athaliah&rsquo;s death is expressed with the Hebrew idiom <em>wĕhāʿîr šāqĕṭāh</em> (the city was quiet/at rest) — the same word group (<em>šāqaT</em>) used for the peace that came after the conquest victories in Judges (Judg 3:11,30; 5:31; 8:28). The formula signals that the covenant conflict has been resolved: the covenant-violator eliminated, the legitimate ruler enthroned, the cult restored to proper order, and the city returned to <em>šālôm</em>. The Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience, reading about the quiet that followed righteous governance, would have heard both historical narration and theological prescription: covenant faithfulness produces communal peace.</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>Joash (also called Jehoash) began his reign at seven years old — the youngest king in the Davidic line — and reigned forty years (ca. 835-796 BCE). The forty-year reign is the same length as David&rsquo;s and Solomon&rsquo;s reigns, connecting Joash&rsquo;s tenure to the dynasty&rsquo;s golden age. His mother Zibiah was from Beersheba — a southerner, not from the Ahab-dynasty aristocracy. This maternal connection to the southern heartland of Judah (Beersheba was the southernmost major city, the traditional boundary-marker &lsquo;from Dan to Beersheba&rsquo;) signals a break from the Athaliah-Omride influence through the maternal line.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&lsquo;Joash did what was right in the sight of YHWH all the days of Jehoiada the priest&rsquo; — the Chronicler&rsquo;s conditional evaluation is precise: the good years were coterminous with the priest&rsquo;s life. This framing (which 2 Kings 12:2 also uses) reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s theology of counsel: kings rise and fall based on the quality of their advisors. Rehoboam fell when he rejected the elders&rsquo; counsel (2 Chr 10); Joash rose when advised by Jehoiada and fell when advised by the princes after Jehoiada&rsquo;s death. The good-counselor/bad-counselor pattern is the Chronicler&rsquo;s persistent anthropological observation about royal decision-making.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jehoiada&rsquo;s choosing two wives for the king reflects the high priest&rsquo;s role as de facto regent during Joash&rsquo;s minority. The royal marriage arrangement was the king&rsquo;s (and his regent&rsquo;s) most politically significant decision — it determined alliances, shaped the court&rsquo;s cultural orientation, and determined the next generation&rsquo;s character. That Jehoiada made this arrangement (not the king himself, who was a child) confirms that priestly authority extended even to the domestic arrangements of the Davidic house during this period. The note that Joash had sons and daughters with these wives establishes the dynastic continuation — after the near-extinction of the Davidic line under Athaliah, fertility was a theological statement.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Joash&rsquo;s initiative to repair the temple was a practical response to real physical deterioration. The temple had been built ca. 966 BCE; by Joash&rsquo;s reign ca. 835 BCE, it was approximately 130 years old. More immediately, Athaliah&rsquo;s sons had &lsquo;broken into the house of God and used all its dedicated things for the Baals&rsquo; (v7) — active desecration and removal of temple property during the six-year usurpation. The repair project was thus both routine maintenance and restoration from deliberate damage. In the ANE, temple repair was one of the most important expressions of royal piety: Hammurabi, Nebuchadnezzar, and the Persian kings Cyrus and Darius all boasted of temple restorations in their royal inscriptions.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The command to collect money from all Israel annually for the temple repairs — an annual levy distributed through the Levites going to the cities — reflects the administrative challenge of funding temple maintenance from a dispersed agrarian population. The Mosaic half-shekel levy (Exod 30:11-16) was the legal basis for the collection; but Joash&rsquo;s complaint (v6) suggests the Levites had not been diligent in collecting it. The annual collection system mirrors later Second Temple practice: the half-shekel tax for the temple became a major institution in Second Temple Judaism, collected throughout the Diaspora and transported to Jerusalem (Matt 17:24-27 reflects this still-functioning system in Jesus&rsquo; day).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Joash&rsquo;s public rebuke of Jehoiada for the Levites&rsquo; failure to collect the levy — &lsquo;Why have you not required the Levites to bring in the collection Moses the servant of YHWH imposed on the congregation of Israel for the tent of testimony?&rsquo; — reveals the authority relationship between king and high priest. The king could summon and rebuke even the high priest. The Mosaic authority cited (&lsquo;Moses the servant of YHWH&rsquo;) frames the collection as a Torah obligation, not merely a royal preference. The Levites&rsquo; failure to collect may reflect the administrative disorder of Athaliah&rsquo;s reign, during which the temple&rsquo;s normal operations were disrupted; or it may reflect reluctance to enforce what seemed like an onerous tax on the population so soon after a period of political turbulence.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The explanation for the temple&rsquo;s damage — &lsquo;the sons of that wicked woman Athaliah had broken into the house of God and used its dedicated things for the Baals&rsquo; — provides the historical context for the repair project. Athaliah&rsquo;s sons (Ahaziah&rsquo;s brothers, who were killed by the Arabians — 2 Chr 21:17) are credited with this desecration. Alternatively, the reference may be to Athaliah&rsquo;s officials who acted in her name during her six-year reign. The removal of dedicated temple vessels and their reuse in Baal worship was the most extreme form of temple desecration — later enacted by Belshazzar with the Babylonian-captured Jerusalem temple vessels (Dan 5:2-4), whose desecration led immediately to the fall of Babylon.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The collection chest placed outside the gate of the temple was an administrative innovation — a fixed, public collection point rather than a Levitical circuit through the towns. The chest (ʾārôn — the same word as &lsquo;ark,&rsquo; though here a collection box) outside the temple gate made the giving visible and public. Public giving at a fixed point created community accountability: contributors would see each other giving, and the amounts collected would be visible to the community leadership. The chest method also addressed the Levites&rsquo; failure to collect by removing their discretion — anyone could deposit directly without going through the Levitical intermediaries.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The proclamation throughout Judah and Jerusalem to bring the Mosaic levy — &lsquo;the contribution that Moses the servant of God required of Israel in the wilderness&rsquo; — explicitly grounds the collection in the Sinai covenant. The &lsquo;wilderness&rsquo; setting of the original levy (Exod 30:11-16 during the tabernacle period) was contrasted with the settled temple period — but the covenant obligation remained. The proclamation&rsquo;s reach throughout Judah and Jerusalem reflects the integrated governance of the restored Joash regime: the king&rsquo;s administrative capacity was national, not merely local.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The popular response — princes and all the people rejoicing and contributing until the chest was full — is the Chronicler&rsquo;s idealized picture of willing covenant giving. The same joy-in-giving language appears at David&rsquo;s temple-offering collection (1 Chr 29:9: &lsquo;the people rejoiced because they had given willingly, for they had given to the LORD with a whole heart&rsquo;). The voluntary enthusiasm of the giving contrasts with the failure to collect (v5-6) and anticipates the Temple tax system of the Second Temple period. The filled chest required regular emptying (v11), indicating sustained giving over time rather than a single collection.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The regular emptying of the chest — when it was full, the Levites brought it to the king&rsquo;s officers, the king&rsquo;s secretary and the high priest&rsquo;s officer came, emptied it, and returned the chest to its place — describes a careful accounting system with dual oversight (royal officer + priestly officer). The dual-oversight mechanism for financial management of the temple is the ancient equivalent of a two-key security system: no single official controlled the money without co-signature. This administrative pattern of dual accountability for sacred finances appears in post-exilic texts (Ezra 8:24-29: Ezra weighed out the silver and gold to leading priests with a public accounting before witnesses) and reflects hard-won wisdom about the dangers of unaccountable financial management of religious assets.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The hiring of masons, carpenters, ironworkers, and bronze workers for the temple repair reflects the building trades available in 9th-century BCE Judah. The repair project was multi-material: stone (masons), wood (carpenters), iron fittings, and bronze vessels. The workmen were hired — paid workers rather than conscripted labor, a contrast with Solomon&rsquo;s use of corvée. The payment system (from the chest collection, through the king and Jehoiada&rsquo;s oversight) ensured accountability: the sacred money went to legitimate construction costs, not to personal enrichment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&lsquo;The workmen labored and the repair work progressed under their hands, and they restored the house of God to its proper condition and strengthened it&rsquo; — the completion formula for the temple repair parallels the completion formulas for the original construction (2 Chr 5:1: &lsquo;all the work that Solomon did on the house of YHWH was finished&rsquo;). The restoration to &lsquo;proper condition&rsquo; (<em>lĕmiddātô</em>, to its measurement/specification) suggests that the repair brought the building back to its original dimensions and character — undoing the damage of Athaliah&rsquo;s sons — rather than a renovation or expansion.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The surplus from the collection — after the repair costs were paid — was used to make vessels for the temple service: gold and silver bowls, spoons, and other vessels for regular worship. The administrative principle that surplus sacred funds were converted to sacred vessels (rather than returned to the donors or to the royal treasury) is important: money given for YHWH&rsquo;s house belonged permanently to YHWH&rsquo;s house. The vessels made from the surplus were burnt offerings equipment — the most fundamental category of ongoing worship. The contrast between this use of the surplus (v14) and the omission of making similar vessels during the repair period (v14: &lsquo;they did not make silver bowls... during the repair&rsquo;) shows disciplined prioritization: infrastructure before furnishings.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jehoiada&rsquo;s death at 130 years old is the longest lifespan recorded for any post-Mosaic figure in the biblical narrative. The patriarchal lifespans (Abraham dying at 175, Isaac at 180, Jacob at 147) are the only longer recorded lifespans; Mosaic figures typically die much younger. The Chronicler may be applying the patriarchal lifespan topos to honor Jehoiada as the greatest priest of the monarchic period — giving him a life-length that signals quasi-patriarchal significance. Alternatively, 130 may be a historical tradition about an exceptionally long-lived priest that the Chronicler preserves without modification. The phrase &lsquo;full of days&rsquo; (<em>śāḇaʿ yāmîm</em>) is the standard formula for a completed, satisfying life (Gen 25:8 for Abraham; 35:29 for Isaac; Job 42:17 for Job).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Jehoiada&rsquo;s burial in the city of David among the kings is a unique honor for a non-royal — explicitly because &lsquo;he had served Israel well, serving God and his house.&rsquo; The dual service (<em>lĕyiśrāʾēl ûlĕʾĕlōhîm ûlĕḇêytô</em> — for Israel and for God and his house) is the priest&rsquo;s comprehensive faithfulness: political (preserving the Davidic line), theological (maintaining YHWH&rsquo;s worship), and institutional (restoring the temple). Royal burial for a priest reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s high view of the high priestly office: in the post-exilic period (when the Chronicler wrote), the high priest held the political and religious authority that in the monarchic period had been split between king and priest. Jehoiada&rsquo;s royal burial was a retroactive honor that fit the Chronicler&rsquo;s present reality.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The transition — &lsquo;after the death of Jehoiada, the officials of Judah came and bowed before the king, and the king listened to them&rsquo; — is the hinge of the chapter. The &lsquo;bowing before the king&rsquo; language signals deference and petition rather than rebellion; the officials used legitimate channels of access. But the king who had been guided by a wise priest now received counsel from officials whose agenda the Chronicler will characterize as idolatrous. The listening king is the Chronicler&rsquo;s negative image of royal discernment failure: Rehoboam listened to bad counselors (2 Chr 10:8-15); now Joash repeats the pattern. Good kings in Chronicles are discerning about whose counsel they receive and follow.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The abandonment of the house of YHWH and the service of Asherah poles and idols — the apostasy following Jehoiada&rsquo;s death was rapid and comprehensive. The Asherah poles were stylized wooden symbols associated with the Canaanite goddess Asherah (El&rsquo;s consort in Ugaritic mythology); they appear throughout Israel&rsquo;s apostasy narratives (Deut 16:21; 1 Kgs 14:15,23; 15:13; 2 Kgs 21:7). The &lsquo;wrath came upon Judah and Jerusalem for their guilt&rsquo; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s standard formula connecting religious apostasy to political consequences. The speed of the apostasy after Jehoiada&rsquo;s death — a single transitional verse — suggests that the officials&rsquo; Baal-sympathetic influences had been suppressed rather than eliminated during the priest&rsquo;s life.</p>",
    "19": "<p>YHWH sent prophets to call the people back — the Chronicler&rsquo;s standard pattern of prophetic warning before judgment (cf. 2 Chr 36:15-16: &lsquo;YHWH, the God of their ancestors, sent persistently to them by his messengers, because he had compassion on his people and on his dwelling place; but they kept mocking the messengers of God, despising his words and scoffing at his prophets, until the wrath of YHWH rose against his people until there was no remedy&rsquo;). The prophetic warnings before judgment follow the covenant lawsuit pattern of the prophetic tradition: first warning, then judgment. The refusal to listen (&lsquo;they would not give heed&rsquo;) is the covenantal deafness that activates the curse.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The Spirit of God clothed (<em>lāḇĕšāh</em> — the Spirit putting on Zechariah as a garment) Zechariah son of Jehoiada — the Spirit-clothing idiom appears in Judges (6:34: Spirit of YHWH clothed Gideon; 1 Chr 12:18: Spirit clothed Amasai) and indicates the Spirit&rsquo;s intensive possession of a person for a specific prophetic act. Zechariah&rsquo;s oracle — &lsquo;Thus says God: Why do you transgress the commandments of YHWH? You shall not prosper. Because you have forsaken YHWH, he has forsaken you&rsquo; — is a compact covenant lawsuit: accusation (transgressing commandments), consequence (no prosperity), principle (reciprocal forsaking). The &lsquo;he has forsaken you because you have forsaken him&rsquo; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s signature covenant-reciprocity principle (2 Chr 15:2).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The stoning of Zechariah &lsquo;in the court of the house of YHWH&rsquo; at the king&rsquo;s command is one of the most disturbing moments in Chronicles — the son of the man who had saved the king&rsquo;s life was executed by that king in the sacred precinct. The location — the temple court — made it both a political assassination and a desecration of the sacred space. Jesus referenced this event (Matt 23:35: &lsquo;from the blood of righteous Abel to the blood of Zechariah son of Barachiah, whom you murdered between the sanctuary and the altar&rsquo;) as the bookend of the entire OT martyrdom tradition. The identification of this Zechariah (son of Jehoiada, per Chronicles) with the &lsquo;son of Barachiah&rsquo; in Matthew has been debated; many scholars suggest Matthew either conflates with Zechariah the prophet (son of Berechiah, Zech 1:1) or uses &lsquo;Barachiah&rsquo; as an alternative name for Jehoiada.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Zechariah&rsquo;s dying words — &lsquo;May YHWH see and avenge!&rsquo; — are an imprecatory prayer calling on YHWH as the covenant judge to vindicate the wrongly killed prophet. The pattern is similar to Abel&rsquo;s blood crying out from the ground (Gen 4:10) and the martyrs&rsquo; prayer in Revelation 6:10 (&lsquo;How long, O Lord, holy and true, before you judge?&rsquo;). The irony the Chronicler underlines: Joash &lsquo;did not remember the loyalty of Jehoiada his father&rsquo; (Jehoiada had saved his life) but killed Jehoiada&rsquo;s son. Covenant ingratitude — failing to remember (<em>zākar</em>) the <em>ḥesed</em> (loyalty/kindness) shown by Jehoiada — is framed as the moral cause of the assassination.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Aramean army&rsquo;s invasion at the year&rsquo;s turn (the spring campaign season, when ANE armies traditionally moved) came from Damascus under Hazael, who had been aggressively expanding Aramean influence into Transjordan and Israel (2 Kgs 10:32-33; 12:17-18). The destruction of &lsquo;all the leaders of the people&rsquo; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s version of the Aramean campaign as specifically targeting the officials who had led the apostasy — covenant justice falling on the covenant-breakers. The plunder sent to Hazael at Damascus represents tribute and the practical stripping of Judah&rsquo;s accumulated wealth from the Solomonic-Jehoshaphat period.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&lsquo;Though the Syrian army came with only a small force, the LORD delivered a very large army into their hands, because they had forsaken YHWH the God of their ancestors&rsquo; — the military disproportion (small invader defeating large defender) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s signature reversal-of-expectation formula. Throughout Chronicles, military outcomes are theological statements: large faith defeats large armies (Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s Ammonite-Moabite war, 2 Chr 20); covenant apostasy causes small armies to defeat large ones. The formula appears in Lev 26:8 (covenant blessing: &lsquo;five of you shall chase a hundred&rsquo;) and Deut 32:30 (covenant curse: &lsquo;how could one man chase a thousand?&rsquo;). Judah&rsquo;s defeat by a small Aramean force activates the Deuteronomic curse.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Joash&rsquo;s survival of the Aramean attack in a severely wounded state, and his subsequent assassination by his own servants, enacts Zechariah&rsquo;s dying prayer (&lsquo;May YHWH see and avenge!&rsquo;). The servants conspired against Joash &lsquo;for the blood of the sons of Jehoiada the priest&rsquo; — the plural &lsquo;sons&rsquo; may reflect a tradition of multiple victims within Jehoiada&rsquo;s family (Zechariah being the most prominent), or it may use the plural for Zechariah alone. The assassination in his bed was the ultimate reversal of the king who had murdered the prophet in the temple court — from public to private, from sacred space to bedroom. The ignominious death in bed echoed Jehoram&rsquo;s death from bowel disease: both Davidic kings who killed the righteous died without honor.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The assassins&rsquo; maternal descent is carefully specified: Zabad was son of Shimeath the Ammonite; Jehozabad was son of Shimrith the Moabite. Both murderers had Gentile mothers from nations that Deuteronomy 23:3-6 explicitly excluded from the assembly of YHWH (&lsquo;No Ammonite or Moabite may enter the assembly of YHWH, even to the tenth generation&rsquo;). The Chronicler&rsquo;s identification of their foreign maternal origin carries implicit Deuteronomic weight: the king who killed Zechariah was killed by men whose very presence in the Israelite court violated the Torah. The excluded nations executed the covenant judgment on the king who violated the covenant.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Midrash on the Book of the Kings (&lsquo;the record of the kings&rsquo; or &lsquo;the commentary/exposition on the book of the kings&rsquo;) is cited as the Chronicler&rsquo;s additional source for Joash&rsquo;s sons, the many prophetic oracles concerning him, and the rebuilding of the house of God. The term <em>midrāš</em> here means an expounded or interpreted account — a written elaboration of the royal annals, not merely the annals themselves. This is the earliest use of the word <em>midrash</em> in the Hebrew Bible (appearing also at 2 Chr 13:22 for &lsquo;the Midrash of the Prophet Iddo&rsquo;). The Chronicler&rsquo;s citation of a <em>midrash</em>-source (as distinct from the standard &lsquo;book of the kings&rsquo;) suggests the existence of an expository tradition that elaborated the court annals with theological and prophetic commentary.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'2Chronicles 21-24 mkt-context written ({total} verses across 4 chapters).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
